         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... turns it ... says: «The Buddha, the teacher ...»</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carlingetal2009"/><citedRange>29b</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... I will report [this] to you in brief || in <hi>taruṇadivāk(ar)</hi> (||) ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:knoll1996"/><citedRange>145, 149</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... know this decisively! Evil ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... through the fruit of the deed ... (of) a blue lotus ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a5"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1957"/><citedRange>255</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... is removed. The pupil ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a6"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... they will be <hi>... ṣāmikāñ</hi>. An earth (?) mine <hi>trāṅk</hi> ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a7"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... the earth mine <hi>trāṅk</hi> ... perish. ... saw him ... handsome ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... are to be received by all beings. 1. The pupil says ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... I am of ... existence. He will not be able to ... me ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1954"/><citedRange>725</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... he will have to tell the link[s] of the <hi>jātaka</hi> [story] ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... || in <hi>paṇḍurāṅkaṃ</hi> (||) ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b5"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1957"/><citedRange>229</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... whom I turned into ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b6"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b7"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">...</seg></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note corresp="#a1" type="philcomment"><hi>(spa)rcwatr-äṃ</hi>: the following character may be the punctuation mark ":". If so, four more akṣaras may be lost in the lacuna; that is, if the restoration <hi>(trä)ṅkäṣ</hi> is correct, still another three.</note><note corresp="#a2" type="philcomment"><hi>(ā)kṣ(i)ñam-ci</hi>: the restoration is certain. More frequent are the variants <hi>ākṣiññam</hi> (excluded here, pace <bibl><title corresp="ref:carlingetal2009"/><citedRange>29b</citedRange></bibl>) and <hi>ākṣñam</hi> (see also <bibl><title corresp="ref:peyrot2013b"/><citedRange>720</citedRange></bibl>).</note><note corresp="#a2" type="philcomment"><hi>taruṇadivāk(araṃ)</hi>: tune name certainly corresponding to TB <hi>taruṇadivākarne</hi>, which has the metre 19 / 19 / 10 / 19 (= 7 ¦ 7 ¦ 5 / 7 ¦ 7 ¦ 5 / 5 ¦ 5 / 7 ¦ 7 ¦ 5). However, this metre is so far not attested in Tocharian A and this fragmentary passage does not allow a detailed metrical analysis.</note><note corresp="#a4" type="philcomment"><hi>tseṃ-o(ppalṣi)</hi>: cf. <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-a378"/> a1 <hi>tseṃ-oppa(lṣiñi)</hi>.</note><note corresp="#a6 #a7" type="philcomment">These lines contain hapax legomena of unknown meaning: <hi>/// ṣāmikāñ</hi> and <hi>trāṅk</hi>. Also <hi>tkani</hi> is unclear, since the plural of <hi>tkaṃ</hi> 'earth' is regularly <hi>tkañi</hi>, while also a derived adjective would be expected to be <hi>tkañi</hi>.</note><note corresp="#b4" type="philcomment"><hi>paṇḍurāṅkaṃ</hi>: the long <hi>ā</hi> is left-bound, apparently as an ornamental feature at the end of the chapter. This tune name with unknown metre is also attested in <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-a274"/> a6; in Tocharian B, the corresponding tune <hi>paṇḍurāṅkäññene</hi> has the metre 4 x 4 ¦ 5.</note><note corresp="#b4 #b5 #b6 #b7" type="philcomment">An ornamental vertical line at the end of the lines marks the end of a chapter. On the evidence of comparable leaves, there was probably another such line following after the blank space to the right of it, and another portion of text to the right of that.</note><note corresp="#b5" type="philcomment"><hi>lyockwā tā</hi>: the long <hi>ā</hi>'s are left-bound (see above).</note></p>
         </div>
